   flattenCorrMatrix <- function(cormat, pmat) {
     ut <- upper.tri(cormat)
     data.frame(
       row = rownames(cormat)[row(cormat)[ut]],
       column = rownames(cormat)[col(cormat)[ut]],
       cor  =(cormat)[ut],
       p = pmat[ut]
       )
   }

## 
##  Augmented Dickey-Fuller Test
## 
## data:  ts_allEmission
## Dickey-Fuller = -0.47868, Lag order = 8, p-value = 0.9828
## alternative hypothesis: stationary

You can see the box plots leaving the 95 percent confidence boundary crossing the threshold from the autocorrelation. From this, it is to note that there is autocorrelation and resulting in data being non-stationary. To make the data to be stationary, enforcing the difference concept is the best approach, and from there, we can carry out more operations. We would be using total_energy. P-value is 0.9828, which is more than the significance level of 0.05. Therefore we fail to reject the null hypothesis.

Detrending technique is used to remove the trend component from the time series to make it stationary

  ts_allEmission_stl <- stl(ts_allEmission, s.window = "period")$time.series[,2]
  
  detrend_ts = ts_allEmission - (ts_allEmission_stl - ts_allEmission_stl[1])
  plot(detrend_ts)

  ts_allEmission <- detrend_ts
  
  adf.test(ts_allEmission)
## 
##  Augmented Dickey-Fuller Test
## 
## data:  ts_allEmission
## Dickey-Fuller = -25.335, Lag order = 8, p-value = 0.01
## alternative hypothesis: stationary
  acf(ts_allEmission) #autocorellation

  pacf(ts_allEmission)  #partial autocorellation

Here, the p-value is 0.01, which is less than the significance level, so we have enough evidence to reject the null hypothesis. It appears to be stationary with constant mean and variance and having a unit root. Although there seems to be autocorrelation present with the ACF showing eight box plots going outside of the 95 percent confidence boundary.

The Naive, Simple Exponential Smoothing, and Holts Trend models did well at equally achieving a lower MAPE of 6.28 percent, 4.12 percent, and 4.16 percent, respectively. However, ARIMA and TBATS model emerged as the winner based on their performances on the test data with MAPE close to 2.31 percent and 2.60 percent, respectively. Therefore, we would use the Arima model to predict the next five years.
